For spherical particles at planar fluid interfaces, the particle size, the interface tensions between the particles and the two phases, as well as the interface tension between both phases characterize the system. If the interface tensions between the particles and both phases are identical, the particles attach to the interface because their presence reduces direct contact between both phases without any additional costs for the contact of the particles with the fluids. For high-tension interfaces and micrometer-sized particles, such as for silica particles at oil–water interfaces, the attachment energy gain can be as high as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
